With average annualised atmospheric global methane mole fraction ( [
X
] ) on the increase , it is essential that emission fluxes from facility-scale point sources are accurately quantified , using top-down ( atmospheric measurement-based ) methods , in order to validate bottom-up ( component-based ) flux estimates .

In situ [
X
] measurements on a vertical downwind flux plane , near to source , can be used to derive a flux by employing a variety of techniques such as mass balance box modelling , the tracer dispersion method or a Gaussian plume inversion .

An unmanned aerial vehicle ( UAV ) is an ideal platform from which to acquire near-field in situ [
X
] measurements .

A number of strategies can be employed to acquire in situ [
X
] measurements from a SLUAV .

In situ [
X
] measurements may also be obtained from a sensor mounted on-board a SLUAV .
